`src/game/scenes/Gameplay.ts:252-278` — `updateMarkerAndAction()` runs every frame in `EXPLORE` state and calls `currentTarget()` → `nextInteraction()`, which does `.filter().sort()` over the segment's interaction array. On an action press, `triggerAction()` calls `currentTarget()` again (another filter+sort) and then `nextInteraction()` a third time. That's 2-3 fresh array allocations + a sort, 60 times a second, to find something that only changes when `resolvedIds` mutates (i.e., once per solved interaction).

```ts
// Before: recomputed every frame
private nextInteraction(): InteractionDefinition | null {
    const pending = this.segment.interactions
        .filter((i) => !this.resolvedIds.has(i.id))
        .sort((a, b) => a.order - b.order);
    return pending[0] ?? null;
}
```

Fix: cache the sorted interaction queue when a segment builds, and just shift it when resolved — no per-frame allocation:

```ts
// buildSegment(): after seg is known
this.pendingInteractions = [...seg.interactions].sort((a, b) => a.order - b.order);

private nextInteraction(): InteractionDefinition | null {
    return this.pendingInteractions[0] ?? null;
}

// resolveInteraction(inter): replace resolvedIds.add(inter.id) bookkeeping
private resolveInteraction(inter: InteractionDefinition): void {
    // ...
    this.pendingInteractions = this.pendingInteractions.filter((i) => i.id !== inter.id);
    this.resolvedIds.add(inter.id);
}
```

This is the single highest-impact fix here since it's on the hot path (every rendered frame) — the rest of the findings are one-shot, on scene transitions.

`AuthStorageService.register()` (`AuthStorageService.ts:115-149`) calls `findByUsername()` → `listAccounts()` (parses the full accounts array), then a few lines later calls `this.listAccounts()` again to push the new account and re-save. Two full `JSON.parse` passes over the same key for one registration.

More broadly, `getActiveAccount()` (`AuthStorageService.ts:158-162`) parses the entire accounts array on every call, and it's called from `Gameplay.create()`, `LevelSelect.create()`, `Result.create()`, and `IntroCharacter.play()` — i.e., on every scene transition. Similarly `ProgressStorageService.hasSeenIntro()` and `markIntroSeen()` (`ProgressStorageService.ts:116-126`) each independently re-parse progress JSON in the same `LevelSelect → IntroCharacter → Gameplay` click flow.

At current account/level counts this is cheap in absolute terms, but it's the "N+1" analog here — the pattern will get worse if accounts/progress grow, and it's easy to collapse:

```ts
async register(displayName: string, username: string, password: string): Promise<RegisterResult> {
    // ...
    const accounts = this.listAccounts();
    if (accounts.some((a) => a.username.toLowerCase() === uname.toLowerCase())) {
        return { ok: false, error: 'Nama panggilan sudah dipakai. Silakan pilih yang lain.' };
    }
    // ... reuse `accounts` instead of calling findByUsername() + listAccounts() separately
    accounts.push(account);
    if (!safeSet(KEYS.accounts, JSON.stringify(accounts))) { /* ... */ }
}
```

If you want a bigger win with low risk, a scene-lifetime cache (reset on `storage` mutation) removes essentially all of this:

```ts
let accountsCache: LocalAccount[] | null = null;
function invalidateAccountsCache() { accountsCache = null; }
// listAccounts() checks accountsCache first, falls back to parse+cache
// every safeSet(KEYS.accounts, ...) call invalidates it
```

